µC0What about the Fighter demotool? For whom did you do it and is it capable to do? Is it compareable with things like the good old Red Sector DemoMaker on Amiga, Moppis' Demopaja or Farbrauschs' Werkzeug on PC??


µC2The idea behind karate went to me around 2002: I had a lot of demo sources on my harddrive, for 680x0 and PowerPC. As people asked me some intros quite often, and as I was about to stop 680x0 code myself, I was disapointed by the fact that most of these routines weren`t able to be re-usable.

µC2At the same time, the 68000 demoscene was really getting into a gap: there was less and less productions.I realized hundredth of demogroup coded demo engines from the 1997-2002 period, with the same kind of effects, the same kind of optimizations, but each one on his own.

µC2An enormous work was actually done in fact, if we look from a "community" point of view.

µC2And so, after all this years, what was left? Most AGA demo from 1998 can't even be seen on a 68060 CGX Amiga, most can't be emulated on new PowerPC hardwares. And I knew a lot of Amiga users in France, that would have work for demos, but had no clue about coding.

µC2So I decided to build an engine that would be able to define an Amiga demo in the more open way possible. There is actually no interface. The reason for it is: no time to code an interface ( I need to drink cocktails on the seaside).

µC2There is only a commandline tool, which read a text file, which looks like HTML (or XML if you know XML). The engine actually builds objects described in the file...and then "play" the "main script" object. There is some object-though behind: for example, no asm effect code stands in the tool itself: they are into the plugins (.Fx files).

µC2The plugins defines the types of class you use to create objects in the file. There is some kinds of devkit on the karate page to create new ".fx".

µC2Thus, "karate fighter" doesn't look at all like µC7DemopajaµC2 or µC6Werkzeug µC2(which, yes, are better tools to my mind from a user point of view), but is actually very close to some modern language like REBOL (done by the same guy that did amigaOS). Karate defines an "interface" that allows complex effects to be used easily.

µC2It is open enough to allow any kind of chaining between effects. I don't want to go further in describing karate, because I can easily write pages and pages. Actually, something like 10 or 12 demos have been done with it, plus some strange Fx like the robot or one that allows to do the VJ. The french demo group "µC0Pure LamersµC2" actually did a complete interface for karate, using MUIRexx on pegasos. (they had a complete demo production chain now, including lightwave5.5 running emulated.). They did a quite good demo for bp05 that was disqualified because they used a png icon to throw it (didn't work on the a4000 used at bp.). arrg.

µC2So my advice is: you have an Amiga ? Download karate. Click on the examples. You were searching for a new Mankind demo? Actually the examples in karate were themselves a lot of work and are worth to watch at.


